<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06155205 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06155205 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Barry Bonds wasn't pleased with his slow start this season, but neither was heoverly concerned about it.;    The Pirates left fielder drove in three runsSunday with a two-run homer and ninth-inning double to lead Pittsburgh to itsninth straight victory, 5-3 over the host Philadelphia Phillies.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  N.L. ROUNDUPHOT BONDS COOLS OFF GREENE  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     In his last 11 games, Bonds is 18 for 41 (.439) to raise his average to.252.;    &quot;When things were going bad, I just put them aside,&quot; he said.;   Bonds' homer in the sixth inning was off starter Tommy Greene, who entered thegame as baseball's hottest pitcher.;    Greene, who had allowed five hits andno runs in his three previous starts, including a no-hitter over Montreal, hada three-hit shutout going into the sixth.;    Andy Van Slyke walked to leadoff the inning, and one out later Bonds hit his homer, the first allowed byGreene this season. It snapped his scoreless-innings streak at 29.; DODGERS 4,REDS 1: Juan Samuel had three hits and two RBIs and Tim Belcher came withinone out of his first shutout since 1989 as Los Angeles beat visitingCincinnati.;    Jeff Reed's RBI single in the ninth knocked Belcher from thegame. Tim Crews got the final out for his second save.; CARDINALS 3, METS 1:Milt Thompson hit a two-run triple and Bob Tewksbury allowed five hits ineight-plus innings as host St. Louis beat New York.;    Thompson, the hero ofSaturday night's win, started in place of right fielder Felix Jose (pulledhamstring). Thompson replaced Jose on Saturday, and his broken-bat single inthe 10th was the game-winner.; CUBS 4, EXPOS 3: Cedric Landrum, called up lastweek from Triple-A Iowa, had a two-out, two-run single in the ninth inning asChicago rallied to extend host Montreal's losing streak to five games.; PADRES3, ASTROS 1: Adam Peterson combined with two relievers on a two-hitter as hostSan Diego completed a four-game sweep of Houston.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910603  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  June  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4C  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  337  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday June 3, 199100155205,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>